      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Sound of Gunfire in America</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Blaine letter on daily emotional wear and tear caused by 190 million firearms in civilian hands in America</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Scourge of Guns'' (editorial, Sept. 5):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Scourge of Guns'' (editorial, Sept. 5):</p>
        <p>The daily emotional wear and tear caused by ''190 million firearms in civilian hands'' in America is rarely discussed. I live in a beautiful part of upstate New York where I hear sporadic gunfire almost every day. Gun owners discharging rifles, automatic handguns and assault weapons out of season claim to be shooting at targets, but how is one to know?</p>
        <p>The incessant, nearby noise of these weapons is enough to make a normal person more than a bit anxious. My neighbors and I commonly ask ourselves: Where is that gunfire coming from? Did the shooting die down? Is it safe to walk the dog now?</p>
        <p>MICHAEL BLAINE  Jefferson, N.Y., Sept. 5, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a novelist.</p>
      </block>
